{"title_page": "Baltic 40", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Sailboat class}}\n{{Infobox sailboat specifications \n|name              = Baltic 40\n|class_image     = \n|line drawing      = \n|line size         = \n|line alt          = \n|line caption      = \n|image boat        = \n|image size        = \n|image alt         = \n|image caption     = \n\n|designer          = [[Judel/Vrolijk & Co.]]\n|location          = [[Finland]]\n|year              = 1988\n|no built          = 21\n|design            = \n|class             = \n|brand             = \n|builder           = [[Baltic Yachts]]\n|role              = \n\n|boats             = \n|crew              = \n|trapeze           = \n|draft             = {{convert|7.17|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|air draft         = \n|displacement      = {{convert|14992|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n\n|hulls             = \n|hull type         = [[Monohull]]\n|construction      = [[Fiberglass]]\n|loa               = {{convert|39.33|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|loh               = \n|lwl               = {{convert|32.75|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|beam              = {{convert|12.75|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|hull draft        = \n|hull weight       = \n|engine            = [[Yanmar]] {{convert|34|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[diesel engine]]\n\n|appendages        = \n|keel type         = fin keel\n|ballast           = {{convert|6173|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|rudder type       = spade-type [[rudder]]\n\n|rigs              = \n|rig type          = [[Bermuda rig]]\n|I                 = {{convert|55.28|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|J                 = {{convert|15.10|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|P                 = {{convert|49.38|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|E                 = {{convert|15.63|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|mast length       = \n|rig other         = \n\n|sails             = \n|sailplan          = [[Masthead sloop]]\n|sailarea main     = {{convert|385.90|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n|sailarea headsail = {{convert|417.36|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n|lp                = \n|sailarea spin     = \n|sailarea gen      = \n|sails other       = \n|sailarea upwind   = \n|sailarea downwind = \n|sailarea total    = {{convert|803.27|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n\n|rating            = IOR 25.7\n|d-pn              = \n|rya-pn            = \n|phrf              = \n\n|status            = \n|previous          = \n|successor         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Baltic 40''' is a [[Finland|Finnish]] [[sailboat]] that was designed by [[Judel/Vrolijk & Co.]] as an [[International Offshore Rule]] [[Sailing (sport)|racer]]-[[Cruising (maritime)|cruiser]] and first built in 1988.<ref name=\"Data\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/baltic-40|title = Baltic 40 sailboat |access-date = 31 March 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200204223529/https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/baltic-40|archivedate =4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://sailboatdata.com/designer/judelvrolijk-co|title =Judel/Vrolijk & Co. |access-date = 31 March 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherwood\">Sherwood, Richard M.: ''A Field Guide to Sailboats of North America, Second Edition'', pages 336-337. Houghton Mifflin Company, 1994. {{ISBN|0-395-65239-1}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe design was built by [[Baltic Yachts]] in [[Finland]] from 1988 to 1999. The company completed 21 examples, but it is now out of production.<ref name=\"Data\"/><ref name=\"Sherwood\"/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://sailboatdata.com/association/baltic-yachts|title = Baltic Yachts|access-date = 31 March 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200204223514/https://sailboatdata.com/association/baltic-yachts|archivedate =4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe Baltic 40 is a recreational [[keelboat]], built predominantly of [[fiberglass]] with a [[balsa]] core, with wooden trim, including a [[teak]] deck. It has a [[masthead sloop]] rig with [[anodized]] [[aluminum]] spars and steel rod [[standing rigging]] for the three spreader mast. The design has a [[raked stem]], a [[reverse transom]], a spade-type [[rudder]] controlled by a [[Ship's wheel|wheel]] and a fixed fin [[keel]]. It displaces {{convert|14992|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|6173|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of lead ballast.<ref name=\"Data\"/><ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nThe boat has a draft of {{convert|7.17|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted.<ref name=\"Data\"/>\n\nThe boat is fitted with a Japanese [[Yanmar]] [[diesel engine]] of {{convert|34|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} for docking and maneuvering. The fuel tank holds {{convert|33|u.s.gal}} and the fresh water tank has a capacity of {{convert|50|u.s.gal}}.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nThe cruising interior configuration provides sleeping accommodation for four people. There is an aft cabin under the cockpit with a king-sized berth and a bow cabin, with a \"V\"-berth. The [[Galley (kitchen)|galley]] is located on the starboard side at the foot of the [[companionway]] steps. It features a [[gimballed]] [[propane]]-fired stove and a [[stainless steel]] icebox and sink, with foot-pumped fresh water and sea water. The [[Head (watercraft)|head]] is located amidships, opposite the galley, on the port side and includes a shower. It is accessible from the aft cabin and the saloon. A second head forward was a factory option. The saloon has two curved settees and a table with the keel-stepped mast passing through it. A navigation station is on the port side forward of the head.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nFor sailing there are winches for the mainsail, [[genoa (sail)|genoa]] and [[spinnaker]] internally-mounted [[halyard]]s, as well as for the [[mainsheet]]. There are [[Sheet (sailing)|sheeting]] winches for the genoa and spinnaker on each side of the cockpit, plus additional winches for the [[Cunningham (sailing)|Cunningham]] and for the [[Reefing|slab reefing]].<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nThe design has an IOR racing handicap of 25.7.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\n==Operational history==\nIn a 1994 review Richard Sherwood wrote, \"Baltic is a Finnish builder, and the 40, with its winged keel, is designed for both racing and cruising. The boat looks fast, and is, but notice that sleeping space is limited in the cruising version ... A second layout is available for a crew of nine. The racing intent shows in the narrow water line, with a light, shallow hull, but with a significant amount of ballast making the boat relatively stiff, and allowing for a masthead rig.\"<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nIn 2003 yacht designer [[Robert Perry (yacht designer)|Robert Perry]] reviewed the design for ''Sailing Magazine'', writing, \"once again Tor Hinders, the chief designer at Baltic, has teamed up with a good design team for the hull lines and rig and produced a benchmark yacht. Baltic's quality is right around the top in this industry\" and also noting, \"we will never see an ugly boat come out of Baltic.\"<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite web|url = https://www.boats.com/reviews/finnish-magic-with-ims-touch/|title = Baltic 40: Perry Design Review|access-date = 31 March 2020|last = Perry|first = Robert|authorlink=Robert Perry (yacht designer)|work = Sailing Magazine|date = 16 February 2003|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200112193757/https://www.boats.com/reviews/finnish-magic-with-ims-touch/|archivedate = 12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of sailing boat types]]\n\n'''Similar sailboats'''\n*[[Cal 39]]\n*[[Cal 39 Mark II]]\n*[[Cal 39 (Hunt/O'Day)]]\n*[[Corbin 39]]\n*[[Freedom 39]]\n*[[Freedom 39 PH]]\n*[[Nautical 39]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.balticyachts.fi/yachts/baltic-40/}}\n[[Category:Keelboats]]\n[[Category:1980s sailboat type designs]]\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Sailboat class}}\n{{Infobox sailboat specifications